commit.message:
bytes_terminate(): speed up by avoiding unnecessary memory copying

This rewrite of the bytes_terminate() function fixes performance issues
of the old version without any known performance regressions.

`bytes.partition()` used before is quite fast on its own for what it's
supposed to do. However, there were two measurable performance issues in
our use of it, if we consider that the `data` argument is an immutable
`bytes` object (which is true in practice, since our read_bytes() method
returns `bytes` objects):

1. See https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#bytes.partition:

   > Split the sequence at the first occurrence of sep, and return a
   > 3-tuple containing the part before the separator, the separator
   > itself or its bytearray copy, **and the part after the separator**.

   The important part is that it creates and returns the part _after the
   separator_ even though we don't need it. Unfortunately, as of Python
   3.11.5, slicing an immutable `bytes` object incurs a memory copy,
   i.e. it is not a zero-copy operation. In other words, the
   bytes_terminate() function unnecessarily copied all bytes after the
   terminator, only to not use it afterward. Of course, it's faster to
   copy only the part up to the terminator - the earlier the terminator
   occurs, the faster the operation.

2. The `include_term=True` was significantly slower than
   `include_term=False`. This is because `bytes.partition()` always
   returns the part before the separator, but if we have a non-empty
   terminator byte to include, we have no other option than to
   concatenate two `bytes` objects. This copies memory because `bytes`
   objects are immutable.

See the benchmark at
https://gist.github.com/generalmimon/dcaec4d005d0d1a87bd237d94199203a
(results from Python 3.10.12 in WSL 2 on my computer are at the bottom) -
we can clearly see both mentioned issues. For `include_term=False`, if
the terminator is in the middle of a 128 KiB byte array, the new
implementation is 1.8x faster due to the issue 1) above. If the
terminator is near the end of these 128 KiB or is missing, there's no
measurable difference between the implementations. For
`include_term=True`, the new version is 2.0x faster than the old one if
the terminator is near the end due to 2) - the new impl has the same
performance regardless of `include_term`, whereas in the old impl
`include_term=True` was twice as slow as `include_term=False`.

close(): ensure that all calls to read_bits_int_*() fail after closing

See https://github.com/kaitai-io/kaitai_struct_java_runtime/commit/feb61fd43e8e3cb4290becf1be84bcb68e4b1185

Validation*Error: only include "at pos X: " if `io` is not `None`

See https://github.com/kaitai-io/kaitai_struct_java_runtime/commit/c9842613c1f9f216fee373b5a526968f260e58f9

_write_bytes_not_aligned(): use `self._io.tell()` in EOF check

In ced78c44, the EOF check used in _write_bytes_not_aligned() was
changed to use `self.pos()` instead of `self._io.tell()`, but this
turned out to be a mistake. Although it doesn't matter in most cases
because it's usually used via the write_bytes() method which aligns the
stream to a byte boundary first (and `self.pos()` is equivalent to
`self._io.tell()` on a byte boundary), there are few places where it
does matter.

One place is the write_align_to_byte() method, where the
misinterpretation of `self.pos()` would turn into an observable bug if
it weren't for the change in 28de847c (which was done for a different
reason) - we're testing for this bug since
https://github.com/kaitai-io/kaitai_struct_tests/commit/cc36a88b3f4b5ae1473e6cae44b464cfea48ae12.
Another place are the actual _write_bytes_not_aligned() calls in the
write_bits_int_{be,le}() methods (even though I think in the current
implementation the EOF check inside _write_bytes_not_aligned() will not
be triggered).

All in all, it becomes clear that the EOF check in
_write_bytes_not_aligned() must not access `bits_left` - it should work
exclusively with the real byte position of the underlying I/O stream.
write_align_to_byte(): clear bit buffer even if the write fails

write_bits_int_{be,le}(): raise EOF errors proactively

Until now, all EOF errors caused by write_bits_int_*() calls were raised
only when actually writing the bits to bytes. Although this would
*eventually* detect all EOF errors (because all bits are ultimately
written to bytes as long as the stream is used correctly), it wasn't a
good idea to rely upon, because both

1. the moment when the EOFError is raised

2. the reported number of bytes requested/remaining in the error message

were very implementation-defined and didn't make much sense without
knowing the internal implementation. Both of the mentioned things would
also differ from how read_bits_int_*() behave, and the whole idea of
KaitaiStream is to make corresponding read_*() and write_*() methods
behave the same.

For example, if the stream position was at EOF, write_bits_int_*() calls
would succeed and not fail immediately either until the cumulative
number of written bits exceeded 7 (at which point there would be an
attempt to write the full byte to the stream, which would of course
fail) or either seek() or close() would be called. So although the error
originated from some past write_bits_int_*() call, the EOFError would
actually be raised from some later unrelated operation (which only
implicitly aligns the stream to a byte boundary).

Therefore, we check for EOF errors consciously in every
write_bits_int_*() call, while ensuring that the error message reports
the same number of bytes requested/remaining as read_bits_int_*() would.

is_eof(): fix for write-only streams

Fix https://github.com/kaitai-io/kaitai_struct_python_runtime/issues/75

Calling read() was problematic for 2 reasons:

1. obviously, it fails in write-only (unreadable) streams;

2. even in read-write streams, it turned out that with 'file' objects in
Python 2, it is undefined behavior to call read() right after write().
This is because according to Python 2 docs, the file.read() method is
"simply a wrapper for the underlying fread() C function, and will behave
the same in corner cases", see
<https://docs.python.org/2/library/stdtypes.html#file.read>. And
according to
<https://wiki.sei.cmu.edu/confluence/display/c/FIO39-C.+Do+not+alternately+input+and+output+from+a+stream+without+an+intervening+flush+or+positioning+call>,
if you want to call fread() after a fwrite(), you must insert an
intervening call to fflush(), fseek(), fsetpos(), or rewind() between
them.

   Even though this UB could be avoided by calling e.g. seek(0,
   SEEK_CUR) before read(), at that point read() seemed to cause too
   many problems with no obvious benefits. The uniform approach
   introduced in this commit is probably much better.

Support writing to 'file' objects in Python 2

'file' objects in Python 2 don't have the seekable() method, so we use
the "ask forgiveness, not permission" approach. If size() fails, we have
an unseekable stream.

size(): fix returning `None` in Python 2 for 'file' objects

Fix https://github.com/kaitai-io/kaitai_struct_python_runtime/issues/72
Add Python 3.11 tag to setup.cfg (#74)

commit.message:
Remove redundant wheel dep

Remove the redundant `wheel` dependency, as it is added by the backend
automatically.  Listing it explicitly in the documentation was
a historical mistake and has been fixed since, see:
https://github.com/pypa/setuptools/commit/f7d30a9529378cf69054b5176249e5457aaf640a

read_bytes(): use previous implementation again for small reads

For small reads, the new code that tries to avoid unnecessary reads is
noticeably slower than the previous code that reads unconditionally. In
the worst case (1-byte reads), the new code is 13 times as slow as the
previous implementation. The potential memory/IO savings only become
worth it for larger reads, where the performance difference disappears.

Co-authored-by: Petr Pucil <petr.pucil@seznam.cz>

size(): remove redundant `io.tell()` (suggested by @armijnhemel)

See https://github.com/kaitai-io/kaitai_struct_python_runtime/issues/61#issuecomment-1107466442
LICENSE: bump year, add newline at EOF
README: update links, use `https://` versions

Fixed `setup.cfg` and added `pyproject.toml`

Co-Authored-by: dgelessus <dgelessus@users.noreply.github.com>

process_rotate_left(): use modulo `% d`, not AND `& (d - 1)`

The method was probably adopted from C-like languages where the easiest
way to perform modulo for powers of 2 is `& (d - 1)` (`d` can be 1, 2,
4, 8, etc.) - see
https://graphics.stanford.edu/~seander/bithacks.html#ModulusDivisionEasy.
In Python, however, this makes no sense, because there's a modulo
operator `%`, which is easier to use and even slightly faster than the
bitwise AND `&` (I did some benchmarks on this).

Fix pylint-reported `bad-super-call`, update disabled messages

See https://docs.quantifiedcode.com/python-anti-patterns/correctness/bad_first_argument_given_to_super.html

Refactor to enumerate from "range and len" as pylint suggests

results in simpler and faster code, see
https://github.com/kaitai-io/kaitai_struct_python_runtime/pull/56#discussion_r847648785
